🔹 Window Functions
Explanation

“In Apache Spark, window functions perform calculations across a set of rows related to the current row without collapsing the data, using a defined window specification with partitioning and ordering.”

Code
from pyspark.sql.window import Window
from pyspark.sql.functions import row_number

window_spec = Window.partitionBy("department").orderBy("salary")

df.withColumn("row_num", row_number().over(window_spec)).show()

9..
🔹 row_number
Explanation

“row_number assigns a unique sequential number to each row within a partition based on ordering.”

Code
from pyspark.sql.functions import row_number

df.withColumn("row_num", row_number().over(window_spec)).show()
Example Output
dept | salary | row_num
A    | 1000   | 1
A    | 2000   | 2
A    | 2000   | 3
Interview Edge Line

👉
“row_number always assigns unique values, even for duplicate rows.”

🔹 rank
Explanation

“rank assigns ranks to rows within a partition, but gives the same rank to duplicates and skips subsequent ranks.”

Code
from pyspark.sql.functions import rank

df.withColumn("rank", rank().over(window_spec)).show()
Example Output
salary | rank
1000   | 1
2000   | 2
2000   | 2
3000   | 4
Interview Edge Line

👉
“rank introduces gaps in ranking when duplicate values exist.”

🔹 dense_rank
Explanation

“dense_rank assigns ranks without gaps, even when duplicate values exist.”

Code
from pyspark.sql.functions import dense_rank

df.withColumn("dense_rank", dense_rank().over(window_spec)).show()
Example Output
salary | dense_rank
1000   | 1
2000   | 2
2000   | 2
3000   | 3
Interview Edge Line

👉
“dense_rank avoids gaps in ranking, unlike rank.”

